# Formatting Reference

Quick reference for structural patterns. Use these consistently so readers can navigate by shape.

---

## Page structure

Every documentation page should have:

1. **Title** (H1) — what the page is about, in plain terms
2. **One-sentence description** — what this thing does or what this page covers
3. **Prerequisites** (if applicable) — what the reader needs before starting
4. **Body** — the actual content
5. **Next steps or related links** (if applicable)

Don't bury the point. If a reader lands on a page and can't tell what it's for in 10 seconds, the page needs restructuring.

---

## Doc types and when to use them

| Type | Use when | Template |
|---|---|---|
| Tutorial | Reader needs to learn by doing — guided, outcome-oriented | [tutorial-template.md](templates/tutorial-template.md) |
| How-to guide | Reader knows what they want to do and needs steps | [how-to-template.md](templates/how-to-template.md) |
| Reference | Reader needs to look something up (API, config, CLI flags) | [reference-template.md](templates/reference-template.md) |
| Explanation | Reader needs to understand why something works the way it does | No template — use prose |

Don't mix types in one page. If a how-to starts explaining the underlying architecture for several paragraphs, that explanation belongs in a separate doc.

---

## Headings

Use headings to give pages a scannable skeleton — not to decorate prose.

```
# Page title (H1) — one per page
## Major section (H2)
### Sub-section (H3)
#### Rarely needed (H4) — if you're using H4 often, reconsider your structure
```

**Heading text:** Descriptive, not clever. "Authentication" tells the reader where they are. "The key to keeping things secure" does not.

---

## Code blocks

Always specify the language:

````
```python
def get_token(api_key: str) -> str:
    return requests.post(AUTH_URL, headers={"key": api_key}).json()["token"]
```
````

For terminal commands, use `bash` or `shell`:

````
```bash
curl -X POST https://api.example.com/auth \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"api_key": "your_key_here"}'
```
````

For output or responses the reader should expect, use a comment or label:

````
```json
// Response
{
  "token": "eyJhbGci...",
  "expires_in": 3600
}
```
````

